If a Policyowner elects cash surrender in lieu of continuing his premium payments, he will receive the cash value, minus outstanding loans and loan interest.

The application usually provides an opportunity for the applicant to select Premium Loan as the Non-Forfeiture Option, stating that they can select it then, or in writing when premium is unpaid before the grace period ends. The application will also state the other NFO options available on the product, and name one (or more, sometimes dependent on ratings) as the automatic non-forfeiture option, which will systematically kick in if an NFO option was not selected at application.
When a policy is put on the reduced paid up NFO, the cash value is used to purchase a fully paid-up policy of the same kind with a face amount that is less than the original face.

Extended term insurance comes about when a policy’s cash value is used to purchase term insurance for an amount that is equal to the policy’s original face and will remain in force for the period that the cash value will purchase. When the extended term ends, the policy coverage will expire.
Would you like to hear about other NFO's?
During the Premium Guarantee Period, Your premiums are level and guaranteed. If you choose to renew Your Policy at the end of the Premium Guarantee Period, the premiums may increase.
Due to $ownerName's policy type, their premium should not have increased.

Interest sensitive whole life policies will recalculate the required premium each year.  If the required premium increases beyond a tolerance the Owner may choose between increasing the premium or decreasing the face amount

If a premium is not paid when due, the Policy will go into default.  If the Policy goes into default, We will send You a notice warning You that the Policy is in danger of terminating. That notice will tell You the premium required to keep the Policy from terminating. That notice will be mailed to You at your last goes into default, We will send You a notice warning You that the Policy is in known address, and to any assignee of record.    We will keep the Policy inforce for the 31 day period following the date Your Policy goes into default. We call that period the Grace Period. However, if We have not received the required premiums (specified in Your warning notice) by the end of the Grace Period, the Policy will terminate.    If the Insured dies during the Grace Period, We will pay the Death Benefit less the required premium payment.

Stopping payments may be the Policyowner’s choice, or it may be necessary if there is financial hardship.  A Universal Life policy in which premiums are being deducted from the cash value bucket will lapse if the bucket is depleted and the grace period is over.
